[{"id":31743,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Elevation in boiling point&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ik</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></p><p>Depression in freezing point&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ik</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ik</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ik</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>Dividing both:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Hence,&nbsp;The ratio of molal elevation constant to molal depression constant is&nbsp; 3:1</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31674,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4-GDVhHoQ8O9aeeYo_KcJ5OKMxgKAMwaYx-bU-eRjRQ.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/MR6JSN-SQBYdWga8POFIzrRqmK8Ax4ciUiEcrn2f8V0.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/IDN5NJ6tANZ6rmq4eXB3v8JMRqWm80d57ieogHk0abI.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/YEOrQrnait0DIaYnTs5KFMHDk2Y7nGqXKokEHmf4N6o.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":0,"solution":"On adding non-volatile solute in a solvent, the freezing point of solution decreases.\n$\\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{f}} < \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{f}}^0$\nF.P. of solution $ < $ F.P. of pure solvent\n\nAlso V.P. of solution decreases on adding nonvolatile solute in a solvent.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aFKF-ULtXrfprVEZA9ut6w_rRWlyOmxrSc1Nd0J5bH0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31644,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["0.340","0.663","0.5217","0.480"],"answer":2,"solution":"For an ideal solution with Raoult's law, the partial pressure of A in vapour is $P_A = P_A^0 y_A$ where $y_A = 0.8$ is the mole fraction in vapour phase. Thus $P_A = 55 \\times 0.8 = 44$ kNm$^{-2}$. <br> Using the equilibrium condition $y_A = \\frac{P_A^0 \\chi_A}{P_{total}}$ where $\\chi_A$ is mole fraction in liquid and $P_{total} = P_A^0 \\chi_A + P_B^0(1-\\chi_A)$: <br> $0.8 = \\frac{55\\chi_A}{55\\chi_A + 15(1-\\chi_A)}$ <br> $0.8(55\\chi_A + 15 - 15\\chi_A) = 55\\chi_A$ <br> $44\\chi_A + 12 - 12\\chi_A = 55\\chi_A$ <br> $12 = 23\\chi_A$ <br> $\\chi_A = 0.5217$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31697,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<h4><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1000</mn></math> ml solution contains <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo> </mo></math>mol of H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>4</sub></h4><p>Mass of solution = <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>06</mn><mfrac><mrow><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo> </mo><mn>1060</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p>Mass of solute (H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>4</sub>) =<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo> </mo><mo>×</mo><mo> </mo><mn>98</mn><mo> </mo><mo>=</mo><mn>78</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p>Mass of solvent = <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1060</mn><mo> </mo><mo>-</mo><mn>78</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mo>=</mo><mn>981</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Molality</mi><mo> </mo><mo>=</mo><mo> </mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>moles</mi><mo> </mo><mi>of</mi><mo> </mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><mi>mass</mi><mo> </mo><mi>of</mi><mo> </mo><mi>solvent</mi><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi>in</mi><mo> </mo><mi>kg</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>981</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo> </mo><mo>=</mo><mo> </mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>815</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>= <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>815</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31768,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mi>Glucose</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>gm</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>&#8467;</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>gm</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>72</mn></mrow><mn>180</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (22 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31821,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>50</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>33</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>80</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=0.50</mo></math><br /><br />Here,<br /><br />i= van&#39;t hoff factor<br /><br /><math> <mi>&#945;</mi> </math> =degree of dissociation<br /><br />k= total number of ions(dissociated)<br /><br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31790,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f90fef14-eba2-4d13-a104-2e1736e1bba9.png\" /><br /><math><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>2.0</mn></math><br /><math><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0.5</mn><mi>m</mi></math><br /><math><mo>∆</mo><msub><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><mi>m</mi></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>272</mn><mi>K</mi></math><br /><math><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0.1</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>l</mi></math><br /><math><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>d</mi><msup><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>g</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0.1</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>0.08</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>272</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br />After releasing piston <math><mi></mi><msub><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math><br /><math><mn>2.176</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2.176</mn><mi></mi><mi>d</mi><msup><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31669,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["\\(\\mathrm{AX}_2\\) is fully ionised while \\(\\mathrm{AY}_2\\) is completely unionised.","\\(\\mathrm{AX}_2\\) is completely unionised while \\(\\mathrm{AY}_2\\) is fully ionised.","\\(\\mathrm{AX}_2\\) and \\(\\mathrm{AY}_2\\) (both) are completely unionised.","\\(\\mathrm{AX}_2\\) and \\(\\mathrm{AY}_2\\) (both) are fully ionised."],"answer":0,"solution":"For $\\mathrm{AX}_2$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{b}}=\\mathrm{i} \\mathrm{~K} \\mathrm{~m} \\\\\n& 0.0156=\\mathrm{i} \\times 0.52 \\times \\frac{1.24}{124 \\times 1} \\\\\n& 3=\\mathrm{i} \\\\\n& 3=1+2 \\alpha \\\\\n& 1=\\alpha\n\\end{aligned}$\n\nFor $\\mathrm{AY}_2$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{b}}=\\mathrm{i} \\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{b}} \\mathrm{~m} \\\\\n& 0.0260=\\mathrm{i} \\times 0.52 \\times \\frac{25.4}{250 \\times 2} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{i} \\approx 1\n\\end{aligned}$\n$\\therefore A X_2$ is completely ionised $\\& A Y_2$ is completely unionised","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31639,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["$10^{-6}$","$4 \\times 10^{-4}$","$3 \\times 10^{-5}$","$3 \\times 10^{-3}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"The molality of the solution is given by:<br><br>$m = \\dfrac{\\text{Mass of solute}}{\\text{Molar mass of solute} \\times \\text{Mass of solvent in kg}}$<br><br>$m = \\dfrac{19.5}{78 \\times 0.5} = 0.5 \\text{ mol kg}^{-1}$<br><br>The depression in freezing point is given by:<br><br>$\\Delta T_f = i \\times K_f \\times m$<br><br>Substituting the given values:<br><br>$1 = i \\times 1.86 \\times 0.5$<br><br>$1 = i \\times 0.93$<br><br>$i = \\dfrac{1}{0.93} = \\dfrac{100}{93}$<br><br>For the dissociation of a weak acid $HA \\rightleftharpoons H^+ + A^-$, the van 't Hoff factor is $i = 1 + \\alpha$, where $\\alpha$ is the degree of dissociation.<br><br>$1 + \\alpha = \\dfrac{100}{93}$<br><br>$\\alpha = \\dfrac{100}{93} - 1 = \\dfrac{7}{93}$<br><br>The acid dissociation constant $K_a$ is given by:<br><br>$K_a = \\dfrac{C \\alpha^2}{1 - \\alpha}$<br><br>Since molarity and molality have the same values, $C = 0.5 \\text{ M}$.<br><br>$K_a = \\dfrac{0.5 \\times \\left(\\dfrac{7}{93}\\right)^2}{1 - \\dfrac{7}{93}}$<br><br>$K_a = \\dfrac{0.5 \\times \\dfrac{49}{93^2}}{\\dfrac{86}{93}} = \\dfrac{0.5 \\times 49}{93 \\times 86}$<br><br>$K_a = \\dfrac{24.5}{7998} \\approx 3.06 \\times 10^{-3}$<br><br>The closest value is $3 \\times 10^{-3}$.<br><br>Answer: $3 \\times 10^{-3}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31792,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> and <math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"At a particular temperature as intermolecular force of attraction increases vapour pressure decreases.<br /><br><br>order of intermolecular interactions Z&gt;Y&gt;X","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31781,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Pure Solvent:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8467;</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>Given:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1093e1eb-3a57-46fb-8153-034c46670659-image.png\" style=\"width: 155px; height: 105px;\" /></p><p>:Solute is non dissociative</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8757;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#916;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfenced><mrow><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mn>0</mn></msubsup><mo>-</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msubsup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mfenced><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>58</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mrow><mfenced><mfrac><mn>200</mn><mn>1000</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mi>kg</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi>mol</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow><mn>58</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>086</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>1</mn><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mo>&#8728;</mo></mmultiscripts></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31664,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"For AB<br />$\\begin{aligned}<br />& \\Delta \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{b}}=2.7 \\mathrm{~K} \\\\<br>& 2.7=1 \\times 0.5 \\times \\mathrm{m} \\\\<br>& \\mathrm{~m}=\\frac{27}{5}<br />\\end{aligned}$<br />Let molar mass of $\\mathrm{AB}=\\mathrm{x}$.<br />$\\begin{aligned}<br />& \\text { So } \\frac{1 / x}{15} \\times 1000=\\frac{27}{5} \\\\<br>& x=12.34<br />\\end{aligned}$<br />For $\\mathrm{AB}_2$<br />$\\begin{aligned}<br />& \\Delta \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{b}}=1.5 \\mathrm{~K} \\\\<br>& 1.5=1 \\times 0.5 \\times \\mathrm{m} \\\\<br>& \\mathrm{~m}=3<br />\\end{aligned}$<br />Let molar mass of $\\mathrm{AB}_2=\\mathrm{y}$<br />So $\\frac{1 / \\mathrm{y}}{15} \\times 1000=3$<br />$\\begin{aligned}<br />& y=\\frac{1000}{45} \\\\<br>& y=22.22<br />\\end{aligned}$<br />Now let a and b be atomic masses of A and B respectively, then<br />$\\begin{aligned}<br />& \\mathrm{A}+\\mathrm{b}=12.34 \\quad...(i)\\\\<br>& \\mathrm{~A}+2 \\mathrm{~b}=22.22 \\quad...(ii) \\\\<br>& \\mathrm{~B}=22.22-12.34=9.88 \\\\<br>& \\text { Now } \\mathrm{a}=12.34-9.88=2.46 \\\\<br>& =24.6 \\times 10^{-1}=25 \\times 10^{-1}<br />\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31711,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>We know that the temperature at which vapour pressure of a liquid becomes <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;atm. is called the boiling point of the liquid.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e34e911e-7db7-4f31-82b5-1b8776b84421.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 275px;\" /></p><p>From the figure, we can clearly see that Graph I is for pure solvent whereas graph II is for solution. Hence the boiling point of solvent and solution are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>82</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>83</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>&nbsp;respectively.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31767,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>12</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KI</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>&#8728;</mo></msubsup><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>iK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;= Freezing point of the solution.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Van &#39;t Hoff factor</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;= molal freezing point depression constant</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo></math>molality<br />For minimum&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub></math>,&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></math> should&nbsp;have the&nbsp;maximum value.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>12</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>KI</mi></mtd><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (22 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31758,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mi>solute</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>GMM</mi><mi>solute</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mi>ml</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>126</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>250</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math><br />So <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31678,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} \\mathrm{X}_{\\text {methylbenzene }} & =0.5 \\\\ \\mathrm{Y}_{\\text {methylbenzene }} & =\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_{\\text {methylbenzene }}}{\\mathrm{P}_{\\text {total }}} \\\\ \\mathrm{Y}_{\\text {methylbenzene }} & =\\frac{0.5 \\times 24}{0.5 \\times 80+0.5 \\times 24} \\\\ & =\\frac{12}{40+12}=0.23=23 \\times 10^{-2}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31722,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Molarity</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mole</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Volume</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>in</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>mass</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>Molar</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Volume</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>in</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>/</mo><mn>85</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67141</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>148</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p>The number of ppm&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solute</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solution</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math></p><p>Mass of solution = density of solution<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#215;</mo></math>Volume of solution</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DCM</mi></math>&nbsp;in ppm <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>148</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>49</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>671</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>141</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>148</mn><mi>ppm</mi></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31656,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["$1.38 \\times 10^{-3}$","$1.1 \\times 10^{-2}$","$1.90 \\times 10^{-3}$","$1.89 \\times 10^{-1}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\Delta \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{f}}=\\mathrm{ik}_{\\mathrm{f}} \\mathrm{m} \\\\ & 0.2=\\mathrm{i} \\times 1.8 \\times 0.1 \\\\ & \\mathrm{i}=\\frac{20}{18}=\\frac{10}{9} \\\\ & \\text { For } \\mathrm{HA}_{(\\mathrm{aq})} \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{H}_{(\\mathrm{aq})}^{+}+\\mathrm{A}_{(\\mathrm{aq})}^{-} \\\\ & \\mathrm{t}=0 \\quad 1 \\\\ & \\mathrm{t}=\\mathrm{t}_{\\mathrm{eq}} 1-\\alpha \\quad \\alpha \\\\ & \\mathrm{i}=1+\\alpha \\\\ & \\frac{10}{9}=1+\\alpha \\\\ & \\alpha=\\frac{1}{9} \\\\ & \\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{eq}}=\\frac{\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{A}^{-}\\right]}{[\\mathrm{HA}]}=\\frac{\\mathrm{C} \\alpha^2}{1-\\alpha} \\\\ & 0.1\\left(\\frac{1}{9}\\right)^2 \\\\ & =\\frac{1}{1-\\frac{1}{9}}=\\frac{1}{720} \\\\ & \\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{eq}}=1.38 \\times 10^{-3}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (8 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31793,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Formula of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ppm</mi></math>&nbsp;is as follow-</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ppm</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>weight</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solute</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>weight</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solution</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math></p><p><math><mn>10</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>s</mi><mi>s</mi><mo>&#8201;</mo><mi>o</mi><mi>f</mi><mo>&#8201;</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>e</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></math><br />Or mass fe <math><mo>=</mo><mi></mi><mn>1</mn><mi>g</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>F</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>S</mi><msub><mi>O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><msub><mi>H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>O</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>278</mn></mrow></mfenced></math><br />56g in 1 mole<br /><math><mn>1</mn><mi>g</mi><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>56</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></math><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>56</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>278</mn><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4.96</mn><mi>g</mi></math></p><p>PPM is a concentration term and its full form is &quot;parts per million&quot; and it also can be expressed as milligrams per liter (mg/L). This measurement is the mass of a chemical or contaminate per unit volume of water.&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31761,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><msub><mi>T</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>iK</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>86</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>83</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>62</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>625</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#916;T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>984</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p><p>So, freezing point of solution <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>273</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>984</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>269</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>016</mn><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>269</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31769,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mmHg</mi><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>25</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mmultiscripts><mo>=</mo><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mo>&#8728;</mo></mmultiscripts><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mmHg</mi></math></p><p>and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"\" close=\"}\"><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>54</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p><p>Now mol fraction of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> in the vapour phase</p><p>i.e.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup></mrow><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>therefore:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31842,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["$5.56 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~mol}$","$1.53 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~mol}$","$4.46 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~mol}$","$1.27 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~mol}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{n}=\\frac{\\mathrm{PV}}{\\mathrm{RT}}=$\n$=128 \\times 10^{-5} \\mathrm{moles}$\n$=\\frac{3170 \\times 10^{-5} \\mathrm{~atm} \\times 1 \\mathrm{~L}}{0.0821 \\mathrm{~L} \\mathrm{~atm} \\mathrm{\\textrm {k } ^ { - 1 } \\mathrm { mol } ^ { - 1 } \\times 3 0 0 \\mathrm { K }}} \\approx 1.27 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~mol}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":31713,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Relative lowering of vapour pressure<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math>Mole fraction of solute</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>Lowering</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>vapour</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pressure</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Vapoure</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pressure</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solution</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>moles</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solute</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>moles</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solvent</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8cb6d3c7-71cc-48df-95a2-6b0a4a86411e-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 117px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>25</mn><mn>75</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mtext>&#160;moles of urea&#160;</mtext><mfenced><mfrac><mn>1000</mn><mn>18</mn></mfrac></mfenced></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1000</mn><mn>18</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo></math>moles of urea</p><p>Mass of urea<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1000</mn><mn>18</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>60</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1111</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>11</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31682,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\Delta \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{f}}=273.15-270.65=2.5 \\mathrm{~K} \\\\ & \\Delta \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{f}}=\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{f}} \\mathrm{m} \\Rightarrow 2.5=1.86 \\times \\frac{\\mathrm{n}}{0.1} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{n}=0.1344 \\text { moles } \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{w}=0.1344 \\times 32=4.3 \\mathrm{~g} \\\\ & \\text { Volume }=\\frac{4.3}{0.792}=5.43 \\mathrm{ml}=543 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{ml}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31677,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["(i)  &lt; (ii) &lt; (iii) &lt; (iv)","(iv)  &lt; (iii) &lt; (i) &lt; (ii)","(ii)  &lt; (i$) \\equiv($iii) &lt; (iv)","(ii)  &lt; (i) &lt; (iii) &lt; (iv)"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\Delta \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{b}}=\\mathrm{i} \\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{b}} . \\mathrm{m} . \\propto \\mathrm{i} . \\mathrm{C} .$\nwhere $\\mathrm{C}=$ concentration\n$\\begin{array}{|l|c|}\n\\hline \\text { Options } & \\text { i.C. } \\\\\n\\hline \\text { (i) } & 2 \\times 10^{-4} \\\\\n\\hline \\text { (ii) } & 1 \\times 10^{-4} \\\\\n\\hline \\text { (iii) } & 2 \\times 10^{-3} \\\\\n\\hline \\text { (iv) } & 2 \\times 10^{-2} \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}$\n\n\n\nB.P. order :\n$\\text { (ii) } < \\text { (i) } < \\text { (iii) } < \\text { (iv) }$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31766,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>From Henry&#39;s law</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi>gas</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>&#183;</mo></mrow></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi>gas</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>835</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced></mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow><mn>18</mn></mfrac></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>025</mn></math></p><p>Millimoles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>025</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31728,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Let Vapour pressure&nbsp;of pure <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup></math></p><p>Let Vapour pressure&nbsp;of pure <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup></math></p><p>Using Raoult&#39;s law and Dalton&#39;s law:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>When</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>350</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>350</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>When</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>410</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>350</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>Solving</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>314</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>434</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31832,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["$0.137$","$0.237$","$0.435$","$0.205$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{A}}=\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{A}}^0 \\times x_{\\mathrm{A}}=$ total pressure $\\times \\mathrm{y}_{\\mathrm{A}}$\n$$\n\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{B}}=\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{B}}^0 \\times x_{\\mathrm{B}}=\\text { total pressure } \\times \\mathrm{y}_{\\mathrm{B}}\n$$\nwhere $\\mathrm{x}$ and $\\mathrm{y}$ represents mole fraction in liquid and vapour phase respectively.\n$$\n\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{B}}^0 x_{\\mathrm{B}}}{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{A}}^0 x_{\\mathrm{A}}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{y}_{\\mathrm{B}}}{\\mathrm{y}_{\\mathrm{A}}} ; \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{B}}^0\\left(1-x_{\\mathrm{A}}\\right)}{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{A}}^0 x_{\\mathrm{A}}}=\\frac{1-\\mathrm{y}_{\\mathrm{A}}}{\\mathrm{y}_{\\mathrm{A}}}\n$$\non putting values $\\frac{119(1-0.50)}{37 \\times 0.50}=\\frac{1-y_{\\mathrm{A}}}{\\mathrm{y}_{\\mathrm{A}}}$ on solving $\\mathrm{y}_{\\mathrm{A}}=0.237$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (23 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31652,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Using boiling point elevation to find molality:<br>$\\Delta T_b = K_b \\times m$ gives $0.5 = 5.0 \\times m$, so $m = 0.1$ mol/kg.<br>Converting molality to moles of solute:<br>$0.1 = \\frac{\\text{moles of X}}{0.15}$, giving moles of X = 0.015 mol.<br>Molar mass of X = 1.5 g / 0.015 mol = 100 g/mol.<br>For vapor pressure lowering, the relative lowering equals the mole fraction of solute.<br>Moles of solvent Y = 150 g / 300 g/mol = 0.5 mol.<br>Relative lowering of vapor pressure<br>= $\\frac{n_X}{n_X + n_Y} = \\frac{0.015}{0.015 + 0.5}$ <br>$= \\frac{0.015}{0.515} = 0.0291 \\approx 3 \\times 10^{-2}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31689,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned}\n& 2=0.52 \\times \\mathrm{m} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{m}=\\frac{2}{0.52}\n\\end{aligned}$<br />According to question, solution is much diluted\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\text { so } \\frac{\\Delta \\mathrm{P}}{\\mathrm{P}^{\\circ}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{n}_{\\text {solute }}}{\\mathrm{n}_{\\text {solvent }}} \\\\\n& \\frac{\\Delta \\mathrm{P}}{\\mathrm{P}^{\\circ}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{m}}{1000} \\times \\mathrm{M}_{\\text {solvent }} \\\\\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{P}=\\mathrm{P}^{\\circ} \\times \\frac{\\mathrm{m}}{1000} \\times \\mathrm{M}_{\\text {solvent }} \\\\\n& \\quad=760 \\times \\frac{\\frac{2}{0.52}}{1000} \\times 18=52.615 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{P}_5=760-52.615=707.385 \\mathrm{~mm} \\text { of } \\mathrm{Hg}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31772,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>)</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>885</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>85</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31673,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Normal molar mass of $\\mathrm{MX}_2=164.0 \\mathrm{~g} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$\nObserved molar mass of $\\mathrm{MX}_2=65.6 \\mathrm{~g} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\text { Van't Hoff factor }(\\mathrm{i})=\\frac{\\text { Normal molar mass }}{\\text { Observed molar mass }} \\\\\n& =\\frac{164}{65.6}=2.5\n\\end{aligned}$\nIf $\\alpha$ is the degree of ionisation, then\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\underset{1-\\alpha}{\\mathrm{MX}_2} \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{M}_\\alpha^{2+}+\\underset{2 \\alpha}{2 \\mathrm{X}^{-}} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{i}=1-\\alpha+\\alpha+2 \\alpha=1+2 \\alpha \\\\\n& 1+2 \\alpha=2.5 \\\\\n& \\alpha=0.75\n\\end{aligned}$\n$\\therefore$ Percent degree of ionisation $=75 \\%$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31659,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{MX}_3 \\rightarrow \\mathrm{M}^{+3}+3 \\mathrm{X}^{\\ominus}$<br />$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{i}=1+(\\mathrm{n}-1) \\alpha \\\\ & \\mathrm{i}=1+(4-1) \\alpha=2\\end{aligned}$<br />$\\alpha=\\frac{1}{3}=33.33 \\% \\approx 33 \\%$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31642,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["400, 300","600,400","300,200","500, 200"],"answer":3,"solution":"For an ideal solution obeying Raoult's Law, total pressure is<br>$P = P_A^o x_A + P_B^o x_B$. <br>Initially with 2 moles A and 3 moles B:<br>$x_A = 0.4, x_B = 0.6$, and $P = 320 = 0.4P_A^o + 0.6P_B^o$ <br>After adding 1 mole each: 3 moles A and 4 moles B gives <br>$x_A = \\frac{3}{7}, x_B = \\frac{4}{7}$, and $P = 328.6 = \\frac{3}{7}P_A^o + \\frac{4}{7}P_B^o$ <br>From the first equation:<br>$3200 = 4P_A^o + 6P_B^o$ <br>From the second:<br>$2300.2 = 3P_A^o + 4P_B^o$ <br>Solving: We find $P_B^o = 200$ mm Hg and $P_A^o = 500$ mm Hg.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31859,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["molality","weight fraction of solute","fraction of solute present in water","mole fraction"],"answer":2,"solution":"Volume increases with rise in temperature.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null}]